  "prompt": "Which food should I not eat after getting a tattoo?",
  "response": "After getting a tattoo, it's important to avoid foods that could impair healing, increase inflammation, or raise infection risk. Here's a concise list of foods to avoid and why:\n\n1. **Processed/Junk Foods** (e.g., fast food, chips): High in unhealthy fats, sugars, and preservatives that can promote inflammation and slow healing.\n\n2. **Sugary Foods/Drinks** (e.g., soda, candy): Excess sugar can suppress immune function, reducing your body\u2019s ability to fight infections.\n\n3. **Alcohol**: Dehydrates the body, thins the blood (increasing bleeding risk), and weakens immune response. Avoid for at least 48 hours post-tattoo.\n\n4. **High-Sodium Foods** (e.g., processed meats, salty snacks): Can cause dehydration, which hinders skin repair and increases swelling.\n\n5. **Raw/Undercooked Seafood** (e.g., sushi, shellfish): Higher risk of foodborne illnesses (e.g., salmonella), which could complicate healing.\n\n6. **Excessively Spicy Foods**: May induce sweating or stomach irritation, potentially irritating the tattooed area or introducing bacteria through sweat.\n\n**Additional Considerations**:\n- **Dairy**: Avoid if you\u2019re lactose intolerant, as digestive stress might divert resources from healing.\n- **Blood-Thinning Foods** (e.g., large amounts of garlic, ginger): Could increase bleeding risk, though moderate culinary use is likely safe.\n- **Allergenic Foods**: Avoid known allergens to prevent unnecessary immune reactions.\n\n**Focus Instead On**:\n- **Hydration**: Drink plenty of water.\n- **Nutrient-Rich Foods**: Lean proteins, fruits (vitamins A/C), vegetables, nuts, and seeds to support tissue repair and immunity.\n\nBy prioritizing a balanced diet and avoiding these categories, you\u2019ll support faster, healthier tattoo healing. Always follow aftercare instructions from your tattoo artist and consult a healthcare professional if you notice signs of infection.",
